    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I saw a note in the manual about how blockages can cause issues. Like, what actually happens to the readings if the tube gets blocked up by something? What kind of stuff usually causes those blockages?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the pitot tube gets blocked, it can lead to a loss of accurate airspeed indication. This is because the blockage prevents the tube from measuring the dynamic pressure correctly, causing the airspeed indicator to read erroneously high or low depending on the nature of the blockage. Common causes of blockages include ice, bugs, bird droppings, or even a foreign object that might have come into contact with the aircraft during takeoff or landing. When a blockage occurs, pilots may notice unusual behavior of the airspeed indicator, such as sudden jumps or drops in the readout, prompting them to perform a visual inspection of the pitot tube upon landing. It's essential for pilots to address any suspected blockages immediately to avoid potential safety issues during flight.",
